## Example Usage

### Basic usage

When the same key holds an object in both arguments, the objects are merged recursively. For all other value types the rightmost argument wins.

```console
> provider::util::nestedMerge({ a = "b", b = { z = true } }, { a = [1, 2], c = "z" }, { b = { x = false }, d = 3 })
{
  "a" = [1, 2]
  "b" = {
    "x" = false
    "z" = true
  }
  "c" = "z"
  "d" = 3
}
```

`a` is overwritten by `[1, 2]` (last wins), but `b` is deeply merged — `z = true` from the first argument is preserved while `x = false` is added from the third.

### Merging defaults with environment overrides

A common pattern is to define shared defaults and merge per-environment overrides on top.

```terraform
locals {
  defaults = {
    replicas = 1
    tls      = false
    labels   = { app = "myapp" }
  }

  prod_overrides = {
    replicas = 3
    tls      = true
    labels   = { env = "prod" }
  }
}

output "prod_config" {
  value = provider::util::nestedMerge(local.defaults, local.prod_overrides)
}
# Result:
# {
#   replicas = 3
#   tls      = true
#   labels   = { app = "myapp", env = "prod" }
# }
```

Note that `labels` is recursively merged — both `app` from defaults and `env` from the override are present in the result.

### Difference from Terraform's built-in merge()

Terraform's built-in `merge()` does a **shallow** merge: if the same key exists in two maps, the later value replaces the earlier one entirely, even for nested objects.

```console
> merge({ b = { x = false } }, { b = { z = true } })
{ "b" = { "z" = true } }

> provider::util::nestedMerge({ b = { x = false } }, { b = { z = true } })
{ "b" = { "x" = false, "z" = true } }
```
